<br>
1) Never join a guild that invites you out of the blue.<br>
2) Never join a guild who bribes you with equipment or PL<br>
3) Never join a guild because the need &quot;class_01&quot; and you fit the bill.<br>
4) Never join a guild whose goals differ from your own (rp, events, structure, loot distribution)<br>
5) Never join a guild out of boredom<br>
6) Never join a guild that has a bad reputation<br>
<br>
1) Join a guild that make it tough for you to get in -IF- during that process you discover that you like the people, admire the leaders, trust the officers and enjoy the guild focus.<br>
2) Join a guild that makes it a point to get to know you before you become a member.<br>
3) Join a guild that embraces you becuase of who you are not what you bring to the table.<br>
4) Join a guild that enhances your fun.<br>
<br>
Borm <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showUserPublicProfile?gid=cornus@firionavie>Cornus</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 1<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(11/22/02 10:10 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm47.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=354.topic&index=5>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Guilds and roleplay</span><hr size=1> I have recently returned to Norrath after an absence of two years and chose FV as my server because I want to indulge in as pure a roleplaying character as possible.  I am disappointed in the number of players who have no concept of roelplaying and this can make it difficult to talk to someone who is making comments more appropriate to OOC.  I am a mature psychologist who is studying the need for myth in a culture and the addictive process that has become a mojor issue with online gaming.  Yet I also enjoy immersing in the game for its own sake and would like to find a Guild that shares my values.  As a &quot;good&quot; Druid Halfling I expect to be excluded from much of the activities and that is OK with me. Some of us are prepared to pay the price for walking a different road.<br>
<br>
My creed does not allow me to kill or join anyone who kills wolves, and after a traumatic experience in Runnyeye I have become claustrophobic. Character flaws are part of life and need to be part of our characters to be credible.  Adolescent immortality concepts are OK for the adolescent but some of us want more from the experience.<br>
<br>
Cornus<br>
14th lvl Druid<br>
